WEBVTT

00:14.402 --> 00:21.050
The scripture reading today is from the book of Matthew chapter 6 verses 25 to 34.

00:24.655 --> 00:33.286
Therefore, I tell you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat or drink, or about your body, what you will wear.

00:34.147 --> 00:38.092
Is not life more than food and the body more than clothes?

00:39.334 --> 00:40.475
Look at the birds of the air.

00:41.016 --> 00:42.898
They do not sow or reap.

00:43.074 --> 00:46.760
or store away in barns, and yet your heavenly father feeds them.

00:48.002 --> 00:50.445
Are you not much more valuable than they?

00:51.427 --> 00:56.495
Can any one of you, by worrying, add a single hour to your life?

00:58.518 --> 01:00.361
And why do you worry about clothes?

01:01.002 --> 01:02.684
See how the flowers of the field grow.

01:03.025 --> 01:11.698
They do not labor or spin, yet I tell you that not even Solomon in all his splendor was dressed like one of these.

01:12.418 --> 01:24.453
If that is how God clothes the grass of the field, which is here today and tomorrow is thrown into the fire, will he not much more clothe you, you of little faith?

01:26.255 --> 01:32.123
So, do not worry saying what shall we eat or what shall we drink or what shall we wear.

01:32.163 --> 01:38.050
For the pagans run after all these things and your heavenly Father knows that you need them.

01:39.012 --> 01:40.914
But seek first.

01:40.994 --> 01:46.582
his kingdom and his righteousness, and all these things will be given to you as well.

01:47.704 --> 01:52.451
Therefore, do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself.

01:53.312 --> 01:57.098
Each day has enough trouble of its own.

01:57.118 --> 01:58.720
This is the word of the Lord.

01:58.761 --> 02:06.132
Thank you, David.

02:06.152 --> 02:07.794
Good morning, church.

02:08.578 --> 02:10.481
Good to see you all.

02:10.541 --> 02:15.748
It's kind of back today, but it's been nice to have a little break from the smoke for the last few days, huh?

02:15.768 --> 02:22.757
I read somewhere that when it gets to an AQI of 200, it's the equivalent of smoking seven and a half cigarettes in a day.

02:24.360 --> 02:28.906
Which sounds bad, but I can tell you as a former smoker, that's definitely not true.

02:31.309 --> 02:33.132
Because no one smokes half a cigarette.

02:33.712 --> 02:37.778
Like, it's kind of an all or nothing sort of thing.

02:38.178 --> 02:39.421
That's fake news.

02:39.762 --> 02:45.515
But today is the first Sunday in the season of creation.

02:46.276 --> 02:54.194
And if you've never heard of the season of creation, that's because it's a relatively new addition to the church calendar.

02:54.306 --> 03:24.292
It started back in the 1980s in Turkey with an Orthodox priest and then some Lutherans from Australia and some Catholics in the Philippines and some Episcopalians in New Jersey got on board and now Christians all over the world of all different nations and denominations celebrate the season of creation during this time of year and in 2015 Pope Francis officially added it to the Catholic calendar and so the season of

03:24.272 --> 03:33.032
Creation is a time, obviously, when we worship God as our Creator, as the Creator of the heavens and the earth and the world in which we live.

03:33.112 --> 03:37.141
And so you'll notice we're singing songs that worship God as Creator.

03:37.221 --> 03:41.330
Our prayers are focused on Him and His creation.

03:41.378 --> 03:52.593
And it's a time where not only do we worship God as creator, but we seek to see our relationships with God and each other and the rest of creation restored.

03:52.713 --> 03:55.497
And so that's where we'll be for the next few weeks.

03:56.238 --> 03:58.741
I'm excited about the sermon series during creation.

03:58.781 --> 04:04.990
It's called Speak to the Earth, Listening to Creation in the Teachings of Jesus.

04:06.312 --> 04:08.114
Jesus was a masterful teacher.

04:08.290 --> 04:18.264
And one of the things you'll notice in his teachings is that he often draws observations from the natural world to illustrate the kingdom of God.

04:18.825 --> 04:34.386
And so he repeatedly encourages his disciples to pay attention to earth and animals, soil and sky, seeds and weeds, vines and branches, rocks and trees, weather and seasons.

04:34.754 --> 04:40.544
showing the similarities between life in the natural world and life in the kingdom of God.

04:40.724 --> 04:49.419
And so for these next few weeks, we're going to be looking at the teachings of Jesus that draw on the beauty and wisdom of God's creation.

04:50.280 --> 04:55.069
The series title, Speak to the Earth, I know it sounds kind of artsy-fartsy, but it's straight from the Bible.

04:55.089 --> 04:56.751
It's from the book of Job.

04:57.312 --> 05:00.658
And the story of Job is that his life is not going well.

05:01.090 --> 05:02.311
Things have fallen apart.

05:02.391 --> 05:05.715
He's lost everything and everyone that matters to him.

05:06.236 --> 05:15.966
And then his three dumb friends show up and they basically go, Job, how can you still love and trust God after everything you've been through?

05:16.507 --> 05:30.962
And in Job 12, seven, Job responds, ask the animals and they will teach you or the birds in the sky and they will tell you or speak to the earth and it will teach you or let the fish in the sea

05:31.106 --> 05:31.807
inform you.

05:33.309 --> 05:44.643
So Job tells his friends, if you want to understand how to love and trust God even in the face of suffering and loss, listen to the earth and the animals.

05:45.484 --> 05:59.922
They'll show you how it's done, which is essentially the same thing that Jesus does in his teachings, that he calls us to look to God's creation and to let it be our mentor, our teacher, our pastor,

06:00.386 --> 06:01.147
our counselor.

06:02.169 --> 06:08.399
So that's what this series is about, learning from Jesus how to find God in the world that he's made.

06:09.321 --> 06:13.708
This morning, we're looking at one of the most famous examples of this in Jesus' teaching.

06:13.868 --> 06:27.250
We're in Matthew 6 in the middle of the Sermon on the Mount, and the setting is that Jesus is sitting on the mountainside with his disciples, and he's describing for them the kind of community he's calling them to become.

06:28.066 --> 06:31.530
And in short, it's a contrast community.

06:32.211 --> 06:37.798
A people whose lives and priorities are completely upside down from the world around them.

06:37.878 --> 06:54.898
So while everyone else is pursuing power and pleasure and wealth and worldliness, Jesus says that his followers will live lives marked by prayer and simplicity and forgiveness and generosity.

06:56.578 --> 07:02.688
Now starting in verse 25, Jesus proposes another characteristic of those who follow Him.

07:02.728 --> 07:07.315
And that is the absence of worry in their lives.

07:08.317 --> 07:21.298
So rather than being anxious, fearful, insecure, Jesus calls His disciples to be content and confident in Him, even when life's hard and we don't know how things are going to turn out.

07:21.442 --> 07:24.967
So we're just going to focus in on the first few verses of this passage this morning.

07:24.987 --> 07:26.289
We'll start in verse 25.

07:27.672 --> 07:31.017
So there you go.

07:32.018 --> 07:48.444
If you're having a hard time, if you're worried about your life, Jesus' advice is don't worry.

07:49.085 --> 07:50.066
Just stop.

07:50.818 --> 07:54.524
which is super helpful, right?

07:55.125 --> 07:57.809
And we all know it's not quite as easy as that.

07:58.691 --> 08:09.449
Before we move on, I want to pause and make sure that we know that when Jesus talks about things like worry and anxiety, he's not talking about what we understand to be clinical anxiety disorders, right?

08:09.989 --> 08:12.754
He's not talking about the one out of five of us.

08:12.834 --> 08:22.645
who suffer from real, diagnosable anxiety disorders, phobias, OCD, PTSD, other things like that.

08:24.066 --> 08:38.482
We know that the church hasn't always done a great job of acknowledging and normalizing the struggle of those who live with anxiety or depression or other forms of mental illness.

08:38.658 --> 08:47.973
For many of us, we even come from spiritual backgrounds that are critical of things like psychotherapy or medications.

08:49.375 --> 08:54.544
You know that I don't personally struggle with anxiety, but I live with depression.

08:55.185 --> 08:58.550
And I've had to seek counseling and medical help for it.

08:58.611 --> 09:03.218
And there was a time where that's something I would have been ashamed of as a Christian.

09:03.362 --> 09:08.792
But now if there's a pill I can take every day that's going to make me happy, I'm going to thank God and do it.

09:09.153 --> 09:16.827
So no shame or shade on any of you who live with anxiety or depression.

09:17.267 --> 09:18.951
That's not what Jesus is talking about.

09:19.351 --> 09:23.058
Now I do think that his words hold transformative power.

09:23.330 --> 09:24.993
for those who struggle with mental health.

09:25.454 --> 09:33.968
But what he's talking about here is really the everyday garden variety kind of anxiety and worry that we're all prone to.

09:34.669 --> 09:39.156
And so he starts by giving a few examples of the kinds of things people tend to worry about.

09:39.717 --> 09:42.702
What we'll eat, what we'll drink, our bodies, what we'll wear.

09:43.584 --> 09:49.874
So again, for most of us in this room, we don't live with anxiety about where our next meal

09:50.146 --> 09:57.995
will come from, although we know that food insecurity is the reality for many people around the world, including here in Central Oregon.

09:59.036 --> 10:08.006
But even if that's not us, we do worry about not having enough, or about not being enough.

10:09.487 --> 10:19.378
And for many of us in this room, we don't literally worry about having nothing to wear, even if we use that phrase, but we all spend time worrying

10:20.290 --> 10:25.078
about our bodies, our health, our appearance.

10:26.740 --> 10:29.665
And so what does Jesus say when we find ourselves worrying?

10:30.266 --> 10:34.413
He says, let me show you why you don't need to live like that.

10:35.134 --> 10:37.878
In verse 26, look at the birds of the air.

10:38.379 --> 10:41.164
They do not sow or reap or store away in barns.

10:41.905 --> 10:44.149
And yet your heavenly father feeds them.

10:45.030 --> 10:47.474
Are you not much more valuable than they?

10:49.954 --> 11:01.205
So here, to help us overcome our tendency to worry, Jesus points us to another part of God's creation.

11:03.027 --> 11:04.969
Look at the birds of the air.

11:06.290 --> 11:13.738
John Stott was one of the most influential Christian leaders in the last century, and he took this teaching of Jesus really seriously.

11:14.318 --> 11:18.002
In fact, he thought that if Jesus said to look at the birds,

11:18.178 --> 11:21.062
then followers of Jesus ought to be avid bird watchers.

11:22.103 --> 11:30.134
And he actually wrote a book called The Birds Are Teachers about all the theological and biblical lessons we can learn by watching birds.

11:30.234 --> 11:32.297
So I know we've got some bird watchers here.

11:32.377 --> 11:33.719
Who are the birders in the house?

11:34.500 --> 11:39.186
Okay, these are the real Christians, so hang out with them.

11:41.026 --> 11:48.424
You also know that here at Antioch, we have our very own Oren Theologist in Raptor Rick Gerhart.

11:48.524 --> 11:49.506
He's one of our elders.

11:50.428 --> 11:55.561
And Rick has literally devoted his life to obeying this teaching from Jesus.

11:56.463 --> 11:59.570
This is what he does is look at birds.

11:59.650 --> 12:14.987
And I can tell you that from hanging out with Rick over the last several years and especially getting to travel to several different places in the world with him, it has given me a whole new awareness and appreciation for the world of birds.

12:15.767 --> 12:25.618
So for example, when I was in Scotland for school a couple months ago, I kept finding myself geeking out about all these incredible birds, which is not, I mean,

12:25.794 --> 12:29.039
The scotch would typically be what would get me excited.

12:29.180 --> 12:39.877
But one day, we were out with my cohort hiking on the cliffs of the island of Stapha, and we came across this colony of puffins.

12:40.899 --> 12:52.818
And I sat there for over an hour, just watching these hilarious little clown birds, like walking around, and they looked like little paratroopers when they come in for a landing.

12:52.898 --> 12:55.261
And I just thought they were so hilarious.

12:55.681 --> 12:59.546
And it was literally one of the highlights of my entire time in the UK.

13:00.207 --> 13:08.117
When I got back and was processing my trip with my spiritual director, he asked me, at what point did you feel most loved by God?

13:09.098 --> 13:11.541
And I said, with those stupid puffins.

13:13.424 --> 13:14.465
So there's something here.

13:14.525 --> 13:17.489
But there's even more than that.

13:17.529 --> 13:21.714
A few days ago, I asked Rick about Matthew.

13:21.794 --> 13:31.908
Why Jesus would tell us to look at the birds, to learn how to overcome our fears about not having enough or not being enough.

13:32.829 --> 13:37.476
And of course, Rick could talk about that for hours and I would have loved that.

13:37.896 --> 13:50.514
But the basic observation that he shared is that the way God provides for each type of bird is closely tied to the unique way he designed them.

13:51.394 --> 13:59.025
Okay, so the way God provides for each type of bird is closely tied to the unique way he designed them.

13:59.045 --> 14:00.367
Okay, so I'll give you a couple examples.

14:00.407 --> 14:02.410
Rick told me about the American dipper.

14:03.712 --> 14:09.341
It doesn't look all that special, looks kind of like a robin or something, but here's what's crazy about it.

14:09.841 --> 14:12.525
It's a songbird that knows how to swim.

14:12.565 --> 14:18.354
And it lives along the streams and the mountains and the way it gets its food

14:18.626 --> 14:27.076
is by swimming down to the bottom of the stream bed and hunting for insects and larvae under the rocks and the debris.

14:27.417 --> 14:28.838
That's amazing.

14:28.858 --> 14:32.503
So how does God provide for the American dipper?

14:34.325 --> 14:40.873
Through the unique way that he designed it that enables it to swim and to sing songs and praise all year long.

14:41.914 --> 14:48.242
Rick also told me about the Golden Eagle and how everything about it is designed

14:48.482 --> 14:49.483
for its way of life.

14:50.244 --> 14:53.488
If you look at that picture, eagles are famous for their eyes, right?

14:53.808 --> 15:00.596
But do you know that their eyesight is so strong, they can spot prey from over a mile away.

15:01.918 --> 15:12.210
And in fact, in Job 39, God specifically says that the way he provides for the eagle is by giving it the ability to see prey far off from its home on the rocky track.

15:12.834 --> 15:16.779
Not only that, God also designed the eagle's hooked beak.

15:17.059 --> 15:18.361
It's powerful legs.

15:18.441 --> 15:24.369
It's sharp talons perfectly for capturing and processing the kind of prey that it feeds on.

15:25.030 --> 15:36.985
And its digestive system is specifically designed to take any undigestable food that it eats, like the grass and leaves in the stomach of a jackrabbit, for example.

15:37.385 --> 15:41.010
And it casts them back up, kind of like an owl pellet.

15:41.186 --> 15:44.951
only the nutritious stuff then makes the journey through the digestive system.

15:44.991 --> 15:50.899
And so the idea is that God's design for each bird is just amazing.

15:51.240 --> 16:04.498
And we could go on and on, but the point is, again, that when Jesus says his heavenly Father feeds the birds, the way God does that is by creating them in such a way

16:05.346 --> 16:12.080
that they are able to find and catch and process and digest the specific kinds of food their bodies need.

16:13.422 --> 16:14.464
So interesting.

16:15.747 --> 16:22.701
And so important because it would be really easy to misunderstand Jesus here if you wanted to.

16:23.924 --> 16:27.090
Somebody might say, well, Jesus says, don't worry.

16:27.170 --> 16:33.096
about my life or what I'll eat or drink or wear, and that just like God provides for the birds, he's gonna provide for me.

16:33.236 --> 16:36.079
So I don't need to work that hard.

16:36.719 --> 16:37.861
I don't need to plan.

16:37.881 --> 16:43.787
I don't need to go to school or get a degree or get a job, because hey, God will provide.

16:43.827 --> 16:44.828
That's what Jesus says.

16:46.870 --> 16:55.378
But obviously, if you think about it for just one minute, or if you look at just one bird, you'll realize that's not what Jesus is saying.

16:56.226 --> 16:57.788
Does God provide for our needs?

16:58.369 --> 16:58.590
Yes.

17:00.092 --> 17:00.793
How does he do it?

17:01.694 --> 17:06.101
Most often, the same way that he provides for the birds.

17:07.202 --> 17:19.120
By designing us in such a way that we can take the raw materials of his creation and work with them and cultivate them and draw out their potential for flourishing.

17:21.464 --> 17:25.650
Okay, so from the birds now, we begin to learn

17:26.114 --> 17:28.539
about the Christian idea of vocation.

17:29.981 --> 17:37.295
We use vocations synonymously with career or occupation a lot, but that's really not what vocation is.

17:37.356 --> 17:40.742
Vocation comes from the Latin voca, where we get the word vocal.

17:41.684 --> 17:44.569
And so your vocation is your voice.

17:46.152 --> 17:49.138
It's the song your life is meant to sing.

17:50.242 --> 17:58.553
And when we look at the birds, we see that God's provision for them is through the intricate design and calling on each of their lives.

17:59.013 --> 18:00.075
And it's the same with us.

18:01.376 --> 18:08.345
He's uniquely created and called each one of us to play our role in his story.

18:09.327 --> 18:12.070
And so here's how author David Benner defines vocation.

18:12.691 --> 18:18.258
It's the way of being that is both best for us and best for the world.

18:20.930 --> 18:26.698
So don't try to misunderstand Jesus here by saying, hey, I don't need to work that hard because God will provide.

18:27.479 --> 18:30.223
That's not what you see when you look at the birds.

18:31.064 --> 18:34.049
They're not lazy animals, right?

18:34.149 --> 18:49.170
Eugene Peterson tells the story of watching a kingfisher perched on a branch over Flathead Lake and he sees this bird diving down into the water over and over again, trying to catch fish, but coming up

18:49.410 --> 18:52.214
empty beaked over and over again.

18:52.234 --> 19:00.327
And Peterson says that he started counting and it was 37 dives before the kingfisher finally caught a fish.

19:01.829 --> 19:04.614
And Peterson said, and he's the kingfisher.

19:09.141 --> 19:12.586
Sometimes that's how God provides.

19:14.389 --> 19:17.714
So when we look at the birds, we see that God created them

19:18.722 --> 19:19.623
He knows them.

19:20.845 --> 19:21.746
He loves them.

19:22.667 --> 19:25.691
He cherishes every single one of them.

19:26.912 --> 19:38.647
And he provides for them not by dropping food directly into their beaks, but by creating a world filled with food and wiring them with unique instincts and abilities to collect it.

19:39.989 --> 19:44.114
Jesus says he's a good father who cares for his creation.

19:46.786 --> 19:49.810
So what does Jesus tell you to do when you find yourself worrying?

19:49.850 --> 19:52.473
Go find a bird.

19:52.513 --> 19:55.857
Any bird will do and watch it.

19:57.559 --> 20:06.850
Because according to Jesus, you don't need to worry about your life because the God who loves and cares for the birds, loves and cares for you even more.

20:09.453 --> 20:13.778
The next thing he teaches us about worry is that it doesn't work.

20:14.754 --> 20:20.703
In verse 27, Jesus asks, can any of you by worrying add a single hour to your life?

20:22.446 --> 20:26.291
So this is one of the five questions that Jesus asks in this part of his sermon.

20:27.253 --> 20:30.358
Basically he goes, so worrying all the time.

20:31.299 --> 20:32.381
How's that working for you?

20:34.524 --> 20:41.234
His point is that not only is worry incompatible with faith in God,

20:41.890 --> 20:44.312
But it's also incompatible with common sense.

20:45.654 --> 20:49.597
It doesn't actually do you any good, right?

20:49.617 --> 20:56.204
And we might say, but Jesus, you don't understand how hard or complicated or scary the world is right now.

20:56.264 --> 20:58.306
You don't understand what I'm up against.

20:58.606 --> 21:02.109
You want me to just sit around and do nothing while the world falls apart.

21:03.330 --> 21:06.393
And Jesus would go, no, it's not what I said.

21:07.875 --> 21:09.596
Go ahead and do whatever you need to do.

21:09.636 --> 21:11.378
That's not the problem.

21:12.258 --> 21:16.764
The problem is you sitting around worrying about the stuff you can't do anything about.

21:18.347 --> 21:26.919
So for me, personally, this has been one of the most practical and useful teachings of Jesus throughout my life.

21:27.920 --> 21:36.071
And when I find myself dealing with excessive amounts of fear or anxiety or insecurity, here's what I do.

21:36.612 --> 21:38.815
I run it through this flowchart.

21:39.857 --> 21:40.818
Here's how it works.

21:41.378 --> 21:47.247
When you're worried about a situation in your life, ask yourself, is there something I can do about it?

21:47.267 --> 21:50.552
If the answer is yes, then do it and don't worry.

21:51.533 --> 21:55.419
If these answers know, then trust God and don't worry.

21:56.541 --> 21:58.123
You see how brilliant Jesus says?

21:59.606 --> 22:03.912
I've had a mental version of this for years, but I never actually drew it out until this week.

22:04.613 --> 22:05.234
He is

22:05.762 --> 22:08.326
He is so smart, right?

22:08.346 --> 22:12.271
He's saying, if there's something you can do about the situation, then do it.

22:13.252 --> 22:18.079
But if there's nothing you can do about it, then worrying isn't gonna change anything.

22:18.119 --> 22:20.683
It's not gonna help you out at all.

22:20.703 --> 22:22.205
It's not gonna make things any better.

22:22.946 --> 22:28.574
So either do what needs to be done or trust God to do what only he can do.

22:30.376 --> 22:34.642
See, because the opposite of worry isn't indifference.

22:35.842 --> 22:36.584
It's trust.

22:39.892 --> 22:46.748
And in the end, trust is our first and truest vocation.

22:48.953 --> 22:54.386
We were created and called to live in a trusting relationship with God.

22:56.066 --> 23:08.239
which means that the sign that we're growing in our faith isn't that our life is going better now than it was a year ago, it's that we've become more dependent on God than we were a year ago.

23:09.881 --> 23:16.208
Like when we pray the Lord's prayer together, that's our declaration of dependence.

23:17.910 --> 23:21.554
That's the full and abundant life that Jesus

23:21.666 --> 23:30.521
calls us to, and I think that the reason so many of us struggle to pray is because we aren't living lives that require God.

23:32.685 --> 23:34.568
We've forgotten how to need Him.

23:37.914 --> 23:47.570
Strangely enough, it's often the provisions, not the provisions, but the troubles in our lives that God uses to teach us how to need Him again.

23:49.058 --> 23:53.143
Which is why in verse 34, Jesus doesn't guarantee that life will be easier.

23:53.183 --> 23:54.184
Things will go our way.

23:54.264 --> 23:57.388
He says, therefore, don't worry about tomorrow.

23:57.688 --> 23:59.570
For tomorrow, we'll worry about itself.

24:00.632 --> 24:03.235
Each day has enough trouble of its own.

24:04.816 --> 24:06.819
Does Jesus promise that we won't have trouble?

24:07.980 --> 24:14.308
No, in fact, he predicts that we will probably every day, which I would say checks out, right?

24:14.968 --> 24:16.370
Most days, there's something.

24:19.618 --> 24:23.843
And what's crazy is we can learn this by watching the birds too, right?

24:24.784 --> 24:30.932
Because yes, God knows them and loves them and cares for them, but things don't always go great for the birds either.

24:32.174 --> 24:46.251
I kid you not this week, as I was in my office, studying this passage of scripture, I heard a massive thump on my window and sure enough, a bird had smashed into it and dropped it.

24:46.291 --> 24:48.594
And I'm like, okay.

24:48.706 --> 24:53.534
I went outside.

24:53.554 --> 24:54.796
I think it's still out there.

24:54.836 --> 24:59.984
There's this beautiful little yellow gold finch that's just dead in the dirt.

25:01.165 --> 25:02.367
I'm like, all right, Jesus.

25:06.454 --> 25:07.596
Things don't always go well.

25:08.898 --> 25:16.850
Apparently, life under God's care and provision for the birds and for us doesn't preclude us from trouble or even from death.

25:19.778 --> 25:20.519
But that's okay.

25:22.222 --> 25:22.823
That's okay.

25:24.366 --> 25:28.052
Because our goal isn't a trouble-free life.

25:30.917 --> 25:41.936
Our goal is a life of trusting dependence upon our Heavenly Father, who loves us and cares for us, just like He does for the birds.

25:43.359 --> 25:44.200
So trouble will come.

25:44.461 --> 25:45.202
We all know that.

25:45.314 --> 25:48.299
Jesus says it here, and he says it again in John 16.

25:48.339 --> 25:54.468
He says, in this world, you will have trouble, but take heart.

25:55.790 --> 25:57.252
I have overcome the world.

25:59.456 --> 26:04.123
So as members of Christ's church, our hope isn't in a life without trouble.

26:05.645 --> 26:11.634
Our hope is in the life, death, and resurrection of the one who has overcome the world.

26:14.434 --> 26:20.620
So Antioch, I have a gift to you today, a short sermon.

26:24.664 --> 26:31.771
And the good news that you have a father who has perfectly designed you for the life that he's called you to live.

26:32.932 --> 26:39.459
And you have a savior who has defeated sin and death, so you have nothing to be afraid of.

26:40.239 --> 26:42.802
And you have a spirit living in you

26:42.946 --> 26:48.290
who is actively at work forming the character of Christ in your heart.

26:50.198 --> 26:51.625
So you've got nothing to worry about.

26:51.665 --> 26:52.850
Amen.

